{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17660004","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17660004"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:19:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:19:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21311"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21311"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14184"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100957"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14184"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21311"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83384"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"191"},{"type":"tags","id":"3841"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"34412"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34416"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34682"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34705"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100957","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100957"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check. She has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes, diagnosed three years ago. Her body mass index (BMI) is 40 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. You discuss the health implications of obesity, including an increased risk of cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cancers is most strongly associated with obesity in women?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oesophageal adenocarcinoma","Gastric cancer","Laryngeal cancer","Melanoma","Endometrial cancer"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EObesity is a significant risk factor for multiple cancers, with varying strengths of association. Epidemiological studies have consistently demonstrated that \u003Cstrong\u003Eendometrial cancer\u003C/strong\u003E has the strongest association with obesity among all cancer types. Women with a body mass index (BMI) greater than 40 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E have a relative risk of approximately 7.1 for developing endometrial cancer compared to women with a BMI in the reference range. The pathophysiology involves increased levels of unopposed oestrogen, as adipose tissue converts androgens to oestrogens through aromatase activity. Additionally, insulin resistance and chronic inflammation associated with obesity contribute to endometrial cancer development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal adenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is also strongly associated with obesity, particularly due to increased rates of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease and Barrett\u0027s oesophagus in people with obesity. However, the relative risk is lower than that for endometrial cancer, typically around 2\u20133.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastric cancer\u003C/strong\u003E shows a moderate association with obesity, with a relative risk of approximately 1.5\u20132.0. The association is stronger for gastric cardia adenocarcinoma than for non-cardia gastric cancer. The mechanisms likely involve gastro-oesophageal reflux disease, altered gut microbiome, and systemic inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaryngeal cancer\u003C/strong\u003E has a weak to moderate association with obesity, with relative risks typically below 1.5. The primary risk factors for laryngeal cancer are smoking and alcohol consumption, which have much stronger associations than obesity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMelanoma\u003C/strong\u003E has the weakest association with obesity among the options presented. Most epidemiological studies have found minimal to no significant association between BMI and melanoma risk. The primary risk factors for melanoma include ultraviolet radiation exposure, fair skin, and genetic predisposition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther cancers strongly associated with obesity include liver cancer, gallbladder cancer, pancreatic cancer, kidney cancer, colorectal cancer, and post-menopausal breast cancer. The mechanisms by which obesity increases cancer risk include chronic inflammation, insulin resistance, altered sex hormone metabolism, and changes in adipokine secretion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Endometrial cancer has the strongest association with obesity, with a relative risk of 7.1 for women with a body mass index (BMI) greater than 40 kg/m\u00b2.","Obesity increases cancer risk through mechanisms including chronic inflammation, insulin resistance, and altered hormone metabolism.","Other obesity-associated cancers include oesophageal adenocarcinoma, liver, gallbladder, pancreas, kidney, colorectal, and post-menopausal breast cancer."],"references":["Crosbie EJ, Kitson SJ, McAlpine JN, et al. Endometrial cancer. Lancet. 2022;399(10335):1412\u201328. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35408551/","Yeo S, Walker JS, Caughey MC, Ferraro AM, Asafu-Adjei JK, Siega-Riz AM. Placental dysfunction in obese women and antenatal surveillance. Best Pract Res Clin Obstet Gynaecol. 2023;88:102337. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.bpobgyn.2023.102337","Kabat GC, Xue X, Kamensky V, Lane D, Bea JW, Chen C, Qi L, Stefanick ML, Chlebowski RT, Chia VM, Wactawski-Wende J, Wassertheil-Smoller S, Rohan TE. Risk of breast, endometrial, colorectal, and renal cancers in postmenopausal women in association with a body shape index and other anthropometric measures. Cancer Causes Control. 2015;26(2):219\u201329. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1007/s10552-014-0501-4","Kabat GC, Xue X, Kamensky V, Lane D, Bea JW, Chen C, Qi L, Stefanick ML, Chlebowski RT, Chia VM, Wactawski-Wende J, Wassertheil-Smoller S, Rohan TE. Erratum to: Risk of breast, endometrial, colorectal, and renal cancers in postmenopausal women in association with a body shape index and other anthropometric measures. Cancer Causes Control. 2017;28(9):1007\u20139. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1007/s10552-017-0931-x"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83384"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21311"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83384"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-28T21:15:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-28T21:15:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14184"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100957"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{